 by assuming that the mass of the sleptons that mediate the three body decay
 are equal, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{\tilde{\nu}_{iL}}=m_{\tilde{e}_{jL}}=m_{\tilde{e}_{kR}}=\tilde{m}$
\end_inset

, and expand in taylor series around the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{G}/\tilde{m}$
\end_inset

 to obtain
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Gamma(\tilde{G}\rightarrow\nu_{i}e_{j}\bar{e}_{k})\approx\frac{1}{96(2\pi)^{3}}\frac{\lambda_{ijk}^{2}}{8M_{\star}^{2}}\frac{m_{G}^{7}}{\tilde{m}^{4}},\label{eq:GravDecayApp}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
where 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\star}=(8\pi G_{N})^{1/2}=2.4\times10^{18}\,\mbox{GeV}$
\end_inset

 is the reduced Planck mass.
 This result shows that the decay width (lifetime) decreases (increases)
 rapidly as we increase 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{m}$
\end_inset

, as expected.
