\begin_layout Standard
Therefore, we can confidently derive the following expression for the gravitino
 lifetime,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tau_{G}\approx7\times10^{28}\,\mbox{sec}\,\left(\frac{1}{\lambda_{ijk}\lambda_{ijk}}\right)\left(\frac{\tilde{m}}{10^{8}\mbox{\,GeV}}\right)^{4}\left(\frac{1\,\mbox{TeV}}{m_{G}}\right)^{7}\label{eq:GravLifeTime}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
where we have normalized with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{28}\mbox{ sec}$
\end_inset

 since this is the order of magnitude required by experiments such as AMS-02
 and Fermi-LAT in order to fit the electron positron data in the first case
 or to avoid gamma ray constraints in the second.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Neutrino Masses
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In trilinear RpV the neutrino mass matrix receives contributions from 1-loop
 diagrams that contain both a charged lepton and the corresponding slepton.
 Indeed, we have derived the following (preliminary) expression
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
M_{ij}^{\nu\,(1)} & \approx & \frac{1}{16\pi^{2}}\sum_{gr}s_{\tilde{l}}c_{\tilde{l}}(\lambda_{igr}\lambda_{jrg}+\lambda_{jgr}\lambda_{irg})m_{g}\ln\frac{m_{\tilde{l}_{r2}}^{2}}{m_{\tilde{l}_{r1}}^{2}}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
where 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 are neutrino generation indices that run from 1 to 3.
 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is a charged lepton index that also run from 1 to 3, as well as 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 which is a slepton index.
 Thus, it can be seen that for order one 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{\tilde{l}}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{\tilde{l}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
